"url":"/concepts/boards#api--mcp","content":"`import_board_definition`"},"252":{"id":"/concepts/boards-101","page_id":"/concepts/boards","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts/boards#api--mcp","content":"Create-or-update the board and reconcile schedule hookups."},"253":{"id":"/concepts/boards-102","page_id":"/concepts/boards","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts/boards#api--mcp","content":"`GET /api/boards/{slug}/transitions`"},"254":{"id":"/concepts/boards-103","page_id":"/concepts/boards","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts/boards#api--mcp","content":"`describe_board_transitions`"},"255":{"id":"/concepts/boards-104","page_id":"/concepts/boards","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts/boards#api--mcp","content":"Flatten the transition policy."},"256":{"id":"/concepts/boards-105","page_id":"/concepts/boards","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts/boards#api--mcp","content":"`POST /api/boards/{slug}/transitions/check`"},"257":{"id":"/concepts/boards-106","page_id":"/concepts/boards","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts/boards#api--mcp","content":"`check_board_transition`"},"258":{"id":"/concepts/boards-107","page_id":"/concepts/boards","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts/boards#api--mcp","content":"Preflight a proposed move without mutating anything."},"259":{"id":"/concepts/boards-108","page_id":"/concepts/boards","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts/boards#api--mcp","content":"CLI:"},"260":{"id":"/concepts/boards-109","page_id":"/concepts/boards","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts/boards#api--mcp","content":"Grouped `/api/v1` aliases live under `/api/v1/work/boards…` and `/api/v1/work/board-definitions…`."},"261":{"id":"/concepts/ci","page_id":"/concepts/ci","type":"page","content":"CI","breadcrumbs":["Docs","Concepts"],"tags":[],"url":"/concepts/ci"},"262":{"id":"/concepts/ci-0","page_id":"/concepts/ci","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts/ci","content":"Continuous integration on RunYard runners — GitHub stays the canonical repo host; RunYard verifies every change with SHA-pinned, trust-aware pipelines."},"263":{"id":"/concepts/ci-1","page_id":"/concepts/ci","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/concepts/ci#ownership-boundary","content":"Ownership boundary"},"264":{"id":"/concepts/ci-2","page_id":"/concepts/ci","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/concepts/ci#pipelines-and-jobs-are-runs","content":"Pipelines and jobs are runs"},"265":{"id":"/concepts/ci-3","page_id":"/concepts/ci","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/concepts/ci#exact-source-semantics","content":"Exact-source semantics"},"266":{"id":"/concepts/ci-4","page_id":"/concepts/ci","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/concepts/ci#trust-model-and-fork-security","content":"Trust model and fork security"},"267":{"id":"/concepts/ci-5","page_id":"/concepts/ci","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/concepts/ci#failure-vocabulary","content":"Failure vocabulary"},"268":{"id":"/concepts/ci-6","page_id":"/concepts/ci","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts/ci","content":"RunYard CI answers one question for every candidate change: &#x2A;*\"would this exact change, integrated with the current target branch, satisfy the repository's declared invariants?\"** GitHub remains the canonical repository, pull-request, tag, and release surface. RunYard is the external CI control plane: it receives verified GitHub events, compiles a trusted `.runyard/ci.yml` into pipelines, executes jobs on your own runners — consuming no GitHub Actions minutes — and reports the results back as GitHub Checks."},"269":{"id":"/concepts/ci-7","page_id":"/concepts/ci","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts/ci","content":"The loop:"},"270":{"id":"/concepts/ci-8","page_id":"/concepts/ci","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts/ci#ownership-boundary","content":"GitHub owns"},"271":{"id":"/concepts/ci-9","page_id":"/concepts/ci","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts/ci#ownership-boundary","content":"RunYard owns"},"272":{"id":"/concepts/ci-10","page_id":"/concepts/ci","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts/ci#ownership-boundary","content":"Repositories, branches, PRs, tags, releases, packages"},"273":{"id":"/concepts/ci-11","page_id":"/concepts/ci","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts/ci#ownership-boundary","content":"Pipeline compilation and job execution"},"274":{"id":"/concepts/ci-12","page_id":"/concepts/ci","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts/ci#ownership-boundary","content":"Merge button and branch protection decisions"},"275":{"id":"/concepts/ci-13","page_id":"/concepts/ci","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts/ci#ownership-boundary","content":"The evidence behind the checks (runs, logs, artifacts)"},"276":{"id":"/concepts/ci-14","page_id":"/concepts/ci","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts/ci#ownership-boundary","content":"Check *display* on commits/PRs"},"277":{"id":"/concepts/ci-15","page_id":"/concepts/ci","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts/ci#ownership-boundary","content":"Check *content*: status, conclusion, annotations, deep links"},"278":{"id":"/concepts/ci-16","page_id":"/concepts/ci","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts/ci#ownership-boundary","content":"Webhook delivery + redelivery"},"279":{"id":"/concepts/ci-17","page_id":"/concepts/ci","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts/ci#ownership-boundary","content":"Delivery verification, dedupe, and the receipt ledger"},"280":{"id":"/concepts/ci-18","page_id":"/concepts/ci","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts/ci#ownership-boundary","content":"RunYard deliberately does **not** host Git, clone the full GitHub Actions syntax, or run a second scheduler. Pipelines and jobs are ordinary RunYard runs — the same lifecycle, events, artifacts, cancellation, and stall-reaping as everything else."},"281":{"id":"/concepts/ci-19","page_id":"/concepts/ci","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts/ci#pipelines-and-jobs-are-runs","content":"An accepted trigger creates one **pipeline** — a parent run that holds provenance and the job roll-up — plus one **job row** per configured job. When a job's `needs` are satisfied it is dispatched as a child run with the internal `ci-job` workflow, claimed only by runners advertising the `ci` tag. Live status is never duplicated: the pipeline record stores *immutable provenance* (trigger, config SHA, tested semantics, check ids) while the canonical run rows own the live state. Cancel the parent run and every dispatched job's process group dies on its runner; a newer push on the same concurrency key cancel-supersedes the older pipeline."},"282":{"id":"/concepts/ci-20","page_id":"/concepts/ci","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts/ci#exact-source-semantics","content":"CI is SHA-pinned. Provenance distinguishes four things: the provider-reported **head SHA**, the **base SHA** (target branch at receipt time), the **tested checkout**, and the **check target** (always the head SHA). For pull requests the runner constructs the merge candidate deterministically — fetch the pinned base and head, merge head into base — so *every job of a pipeline tests the identical tree*, and CI honestly tests the integration result rather than the raw branch head. A conflicted merge is a first-class blocked conclusion (`action_required` on the check), never a silent fallback to testing the head."},"283":{"id":"/concepts/ci-21","page_id":"/concepts/ci","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts/ci#trust-model-and-fork-security","content":"Repositories connect **disabled** and **untrusted** by default; an admin enables CI and sets the trust policy per repository."},"284":{"id":"/concepts/ci-22","page_id":"/concepts/ci","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts/ci#trust-model-and-fork-security","content":"**Config comes from the trusted base.** For pull requests, `.runyard/ci.yml` is loaded from the base branch head — never the PR head — and pinned by SHA into the pipeline's provenance. A fork cannot change what CI runs by editing the config in its own branch."},"285":{"id":"/concepts/ci-23","page_id":"/concepts/ci","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts/ci#trust-model-and-fork-security","content":"**Fork PRs are always untrusted**, regardless of repository trust: they receive **no repository secrets** and cannot request native host execution. Their native jobs are policy-skipped with an explicit `action_required` check."},"286":{"id":"/concepts/ci-24","page_id":"/concepts/ci","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts/ci#trust-model-and-fork-security","content":"**Native execution is doubly gated**: the repo's trust policy must allow it *and* the runner must opt in with `RUNYARD_RUNNER_CI_NATIVE=1`. Without both, jobs run only through the Dagger executor or are blocked."},"287":{"id":"/concepts/ci-25","page_id":"/concepts/ci","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts/ci#trust-model-and-fork-security","content":"**Installation tokens are minted just in time**, scoped to one repository and the minimum permissions, cached only in memory, and never stored in the database, logs, events, or artifacts. The runner's git credential is minted per job over the authenticated runner protocol and expires within the hour."},"288":{"id":"/concepts/ci-26","page_id":"/concepts/ci","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts/ci#failure-vocabulary","content":"Job outcomes reuse the run failure classes, and the GitHub check mapping keeps code failure distinguishable from infrastructure failure:"},"289":{"id":"/concepts/ci-27","page_id":"/concepts/ci","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts/ci#failure-vocabulary","content":"Run outcome"},"290":{"id":"/concepts/ci-28","page_id":"/concepts/ci","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts/ci#failure-vocabulary","content":"Check conclusion"},"291":{"id":"/concepts/ci-29","page_id":"/concepts/ci","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts/ci#failure-vocabulary","content":"Meaning"},"292":{"id":"/concepts/ci-30","page_id":"/concepts/ci","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts/ci#failure-vocabulary","content":"`succeeded`"},"293":{"id":"/concepts/ci-31","page_id":"/concepts/ci","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts/ci#failure-vocabulary","content":"`success`"},"294":{"id":"/concepts/ci-32","page_id":"/concepts/ci","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts/ci#failure-vocabulary","content":"Commands exited 0"},"295":{"id":"/concepts/ci-33","page_id":"/concepts/ci","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts/ci#failure-vocabulary","content":"`failed`"},"296":{"id":"/concepts/ci-34","page_id":"/concepts/ci","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts/ci#failure-vocabulary","content":"`failure`"},"297":{"id":"/concepts/ci-35","page_id":"/concepts/ci","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts/ci#failure-vocabulary","content":"The code/tests failed (annotations extracted from `file:line` output)"},"298":{"id":"/concepts/ci-36","page_id":"/concepts/ci","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts/ci#failure-vocabulary","content":"`timed_out`"},"299":{"id":"/concepts/ci-37","page_id":"/concepts/ci","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts/ci#failure-vocabulary","content":"`timed_out`"},"300":{"id":"/concepts/ci-38","page_id":"/concepts/ci","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts/ci#failure-vocabulary","content":"Exceeded the job's `timeoutMinutes`"},"301":{"id":"/concepts/ci-39","page_id":"/concepts/ci","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts/ci#failure-vocabulary","content":"`cancelled`"},"302":{"id":"/concepts/ci-40","page_id":"/concepts/ci","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts/ci#failure-vocabulary","content":"`cancelled`"},"303":{"id":"/concepts/ci-41","page_id":"/concepts/ci","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts/ci#failure-vocabulary","content":"Operator cancel or cancel-superseded"},"304":{"id":"/concepts/ci-42","page_id":"/concepts/ci","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts/ci#failure-vocabulary","content":"`infra_unavailable`"},"305":{"id":"/concepts/ci-43","page_id":"/concepts/ci","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts/ci#failure-vocabulary","content":"`action_required`"},"306":{"id":"/concepts/ci-44","page_id":"/c