yard-mcp server.\" />"],[7,"<Card title=\"Quickstart\" href=\"./quickstart\" description=\"Install the Hub, start a runner, and run your first workflow.\" />"],[13,"1\\. Install the Hub"],[1188,"1\\. Register a GitHub App"],[1107,"10 / minute"],[1189,"2\\. Configure the hub"],[14,"2\\. Sign in with the bootstrap token"],[1190,"3\\. Connect and enable repositories"],[15,"3\\. Install the CLI and log in"],[1109,"30 / minute"],[1356,"32-byte key (base64/hex) for the encrypted secrets store. Keep it safe — rotating it makes stored secrets unreadable"],[16,"4\\. Start a runner"],[1191,"4\\. Write `.runyard/ci.yml`"],[1549,"401 / 403 responses"],[17,"5\\. Run the hello workflow"],[1192,"5\\. Set up a CI runner"],[1195,"6\\. Dogfood and recovery surfaces"],[18,"6\\. Watch the run and read the results"],[1111,"60 / minute"],[1113,"60 / minute"],[159,"A **board** is a durable, configured view over work items: lane definitions in operator language, an optional project scope, and the workflows it suggests launching from tickets. Boards make the Work surface (`/app#work`) a **software factory**: tickets are the durable asks, workflows execute them, and linked runs move tickets across the board as they progress."],[370,"A **post-run hook profile** is an admin-authored recipe for an optional side effect — publishing static output, pushing a work branch, calling a webhook — that runs *after* a run has produced its verified artifacts and its gates have passed. Hooks separate \"the work succeeded\" from \"the side effect happened\": callers opt in per run, and hook outcomes never rewrite a run's status."],[535,"A **run** is a single execution of a workflow with a JSON input. Runs are created from the API, MCP, web app, CLI, a schedule, or a workflow endpoint; a runner claims each queued run and executes it, streaming events, logs, and artifacts back to the Hub as the durable record."],[492,"A **runner** is a machine that executes runs. Runners run the Runyard runner process, which claims queued runs from the Hub and executes each workflow via the **Smithers engine** (`smithers up <workflow> --input <json>`), spawning the local agent CLI as the worker. Nothing is faked: the agent runs on the runner's machine, and the Hub is the durable record — events stream back as run events, and outputs and traces are uploaded as artifacts."],[620,"A **schedule** runs a workflow automatically: either recurring on a **cron** cadence or once at a fixed **runAt** timestamp. Each fire creates a completely ordinary run with the schedule's stored input — it appears in run lists, honors the workflow's approval policy, and is executed by whatever runner matches."],[203,"A **transition** is a cross-lane move on the board (e.g. Ready → In motion). By default every move a work-item PATCH proposes is allowed — that's what today's Work board does. Adding a `transitions[]` entry to a lane turns it into an **allow-list**: the move is permitted only when the caller matches one of the listed channels."],[774,"A **work item*&#x2A; (ticket) is the durable unit of company work: &#x2A;\"Make pause/resume fully supported\"&#x2A;, &#x2A;\"Fix the flaky release gate\"*. It is deliberately distinct from the two execution concepts:"],[872,"A **workflow package** is a portable `.runyard-workflow.json` file for moving a workflow between Hubs. Exports contain source bytes, metadata, requirements, and content/workflow hashes — never secret values. Imports publish the source as a new immutable bundle and create the workflow **disabled by default**, so an admin can configure and preflight it locally before enabling it. `validate` and `preview` let you check a package without writing anything."],[850,"A **workflow** is the unit of the Runyard catalog: a named, versioned definition of something an agent can do. Each workflow has a slug, a display name and description, input/output schemas, and a source program that the runner executes. In older code and database tables the same object is called a *capability* — that is the legacy/internal synonym; user-facing surfaces say workflow."],[219,"A board **definition** is a portable JSON document describing a whole kanban — lanes, statuses, triggers, guards, transition policy, `defaultWorkflows`, and optional `schedules[]` (see Schedules). Definitions are the write path agents use to provision or reconcile boards; the DB row is one *instance* of a definition."],[112,"A card's `status` is only ever `pending` or `resolved`. What was decided and by what live in separate fields:"],[1164,"A creator can make a card timed by supplying `timeoutMs` or `timeoutAt`, optionally with a `fallback` decision (`approve` or `reject`) — via `POST /api/approvals` or the `create_approval` MCP tool:"],[794,"A deliverable exists and needs inspection."],[1478,"A deployed Hub checks the public GitHub Releases API passively (outbound-only, `UPDATE_CHECK_ENABLED`, default on) and shows admins an update badge."],[179,"A disabled-by-default schedule, `runyard-daily-roadmap-shaping`, is pinned to `0 9 * * *` in `America/New_York` and runs `product-workflow` with `execute: true`."],[403,"A failed hook never rewrites a successful run into a failed one: the run keeps its own status and the hook results ride in the run output, aggregated into one headline hook status. `POST /api/hooks/{slug}/validate` is the admin dry-run: it reports `hook_config_required` with missing secret *names* only."],[1103,"A few endpoints are rate-limited per client IP (over the limit returns `429`):"],[103,"A gated side effect asking permission before it runs."],[145,"A held run is cancelled, never failed."],[208,"A human or an authenticated token that hasn't declared a workflow/run origin (the default for any PATCH)."],[181,"A human reviews the resulting branch and explicitly promotes only accepted work into `main`."],[419,"A map of the core Runyard concepts and how they fit together."],[954,"A metered, resumable run end to end:"],[1610,"A minimal, real example"],[721,"A normal person or agent: read everything, run workflows, decide approvals. No admin or runner rights."],[625,"A portable board definition can carry a `schedules[]` array. Importing the definition creates each listed schedule keyed by `board:<slug>:<schedule-slug>` so re-imports reconcile in-place instead of duplicating cron jobs. The optional `laneId` on a definition schedule marks which lane's trigger the schedule backs — the factory template uses it for the \"Ready → In motion\" nightly smoke check. This is the write path a board's lane trigger uses to hook into the existing schedule surface without a second round-trip."],[1563,"A quality gate (tests, lint, typecheck, build, eval) failed inside the workflow."],[1554,"A queued run means no runner has claimed it — either no runner is online, or none matches the run's required tags / requested location (`local` vs `vps`/`remote`)."],[216,"A role slug: `manual`, `human`, `agent`, `runner`, `schedule`, `workflow`, `system`."],[776,"a run is **one execution attempt** of a workflow."],[1546,"A run is in `waiting_approval`"],[1545,"A run is stuck in `queued`"],[669,"A run receives the union of:"],[579,"A run request may include `responseEndpoint: {type: \"http\" | \"telegram\", config}` so the terminal-state reply is delivered to the caller when the run finishes. Delivery state is reported in `responseEndpoints[]` on `GET /api/runs/{id}`; polling that endpoint remains the canonical fallback."],[1555,"A runner is considered offline after \\~30 seconds without a heartbeat. If the runner should be online, check its service logs on the runner host:"],[1318,"A running Hub also serves its own **client** install script at\n`https://hub.example.com/install.sh` (plus the CLI tarball at `/cli.tgz`). That\none installs the `runyard` CLI and `runyard-mcp` on a workstation — see\nthe CLI guide."],[2,"A self-hosted control plane for agent runs — workflows in, durable runs, logs, artifacts, and approvals out."],[334,"A specific artifact."],[214,"A stable actor label: a token name, a run id (`run:<id>`), or a specific caller identity."],[699,"A token carries one or more scopes; each endpoint declares which scopes may call it."],[444,"A usage record is one observed model call:"],[777,"A work item can use one workflow, many workflows, or none yet. Many runs can attach to one work item; a run belongs to at most one work item, and old runs can stay unlinked. Crucially, **there is no failed ticket state** — run failures are execution facts, not ticket verdicts. A failed linked run parks its ticket in `blocked` with an explicit reason (see Boards → Runs move tickets); humans and agents can always re-park or retry."],[851,"A workflow definition carries:"],[56,"A workflow definition declares `requiredAgents` and `requiredSkills` as lists of catalog slugs; `describe_workflow` reports them alongside the schemas so a caller can see what a workflow depends on before running it. Workflow package exports record these requirements, and import preview reports whether the target Hub satisfies them."],[775,"a workflow is a reusable **recipe**;"],[99,"A workflow paused at a gate; the decision releases or denies that step."],[210,"A workflow slug — set `workflowSlug` on the PATCH body (or the run whose status change is driving the move)."],[499,"A workflow's `requiredRunnerTags` must all be present on the runner."],[1091,"Abandon the negotiation"],[1440,"Admin & updates"],[1593,"Admin actions (creating workflows, secrets, tokens, schedules) need `admin`; running workflows needs `api` or `mcp`; the runner protocol needs `runner`. Ask a Hub admin for a token with the right scopes."],[358,"Admin and setup views."],[417,"Admin readiness dry-run."],[1281,"Admin-scoped commands:"],[891,"Admin; disables."],[918,"Admin; imports disabled."],[915,"Admin; nothing written."],[829,"Admin; prefer `status: \"archived\"`."],[767,"Admin; who did what, most recent first."],[66,"Admin."],[69,"Admin."],[74,"Admin."],[77,"Admin."],[