ted trigger creates one **pipeline** — a parent run that holds provenance and the job roll-up — plus one **job row** per configured job. When a job's `needs` are satisfied it is dispatched as a child run with the internal `ci-job` workflow, claimed only by runners advertising the `ci` tag. Live status is never duplicated: the pipeline record stores *immutable provenance* (trigger, config SHA, tested semantics, check ids) while the canonical run rows own the live state. Cancel the parent run and every dispatched job's process group dies on its runner; a newer push on the same concurrency key cancel-supersedes the older pipeline."],[1126,"An approval is a declared question with a declared consequence. Cards carry an *ask* — who is asked, what approving does, and why a human is needed — and every surface renders that stored ask verbatim. A run held on a card sits in `waiting_approval` and is never failed or age-reaped for waiting."],[111,"An ask without both `action` and `reason` is treated as absent; such cards fall back to a heuristic ask explicitly marked `derived: true`, so a guessed question is never presented as an authored one."],[316,"An invalid `.runyard/ci.yml` still reaches the PR as a failed `runyard/ci` check carrying the validation errors — configuration mistakes are visible where the author is looking, not swallowed by the hub."],[463,"An invalid budget is rejected with `400 budget_invalid` at creation (and surfaces as a preflight blocker in negotiation) — a requested cap is never silently dropped."],[312,"An upstream `needs` job did not succeed"],[1322,"And the runner unit (`deploy/runyard-runner.service`):"],[1087,"Answer questions: `input` is shallow-merged (a `null` value deletes a key; `replaceInput: true` replaces it), then re-preflighted"],[105,"Any ad-hoc approval raised via the API."],[1215,"Any RunYard runner becomes a CI runner by opting in:"],[237,"Any subset; `slug` is immutable."],[826,"Any subset; move lanes by setting `status`."],[45,"API & MCP"],[94,"API & MCP"],[158,"API & MCP"],[369,"API & MCP"],[491,"API & MCP"],[534,"API & MCP"],[619,"API & MCP"],[666,"API & MCP"],[696,"API & MCP"],[773,"API & MCP"],[849,"API & MCP"],[961,"API groups and `/api/v1` aliases"],[1152,"Applied as a deny with your note attached; the workflow's own deny path decides what happens next."],[1153,"Applied as a deny; the workflow's deny path decides what happens next."],[88,"Approval cards - kinds, the ask contract, resolutions, timed approvals with fallbacks, and per-kind consequences."],[361,"Approval cards carry `deepLink` (the card) and `deepLinkRun` (the linked run), and their `context` includes workflow and run deep links."],[1124,"Approval cards with buttons"],[1497,"Approval gating"],[350,"Approval inbox / one card."],[727,"Approval inboxes and bots that only decide."],[87,"Approvals"],[964,"Approvals"],[1245,"Approvals"],[1416,"Approvals"],[38,"Approvals — put human checkpoints in front of dangerous work."],[1116,"Approvals and Telegram"],[1163,"Approvals are blocking by default: with no timer configured, nothing happens until someone decides, and a linked run is held open indefinitely."],[761,"Approvals-scoped Telegram session."],[1143,"Approve"],[1074,"Approve — a held run is released"],[737,"Approving from Telegram uses `POST /api/auth/telegram-webapp&#x60;, which verifies Telegram's signed init data against the configured bot and allowlisted users, then issues a session scoped to **`approvals` only** — narrower than any token session. A Telegram session can list and resolve approval cards but cannot start runs or touch admin surfaces."],[1418,"Artifacts"],[946,"Ask the Hub's administrator for a scoped access token (admins issue them from the Connect tab or `POST /api/tokens`). Agents typically need `api` and/or `mcp` — nothing more. Send it as `Authorization: Bearer <token>` on every HTTP call, or configure it for the MCP server. Never ask for or expect the bootstrap/admin token."],[1442,"Assistant"],[804,"Attach runs three ways:"],[1061,"Audit log (admin)"],[930,"Auth"],[924,"Auth expectations"],[958,"Authenticate, discover, and drive workflow runs over the Runyard Hub's HTTP API."],[959,"Authentication"],[1607,"Authoring workflows"],[37,"Authoring workflows — create your own workflows over the API or MCP."],[101,"Autonomous recovery gave up; a human records how to proceed."],[1381,"Back this directory up. The runner workspace, by contrast, is disposable\nscratch space — outputs and event traces are uploaded to the Hub as artifacts."],[690,"Bearer-token authentication, the scope vocabulary and presets (including read-only), the bootstrap token, and how browser and Telegram sessions work."],[570,"Before anything is enqueued, Runyard can run a **deterministic preflight**: schema checks on required input fields, runner/tag availability, secret presence, hook eligibility, and workflow source resolution. The result is `ready`, `needs_input` (with `questions[]` the caller can answer), or `blocked` (with `blockers[]` only an operator can fix), plus warnings, suggested defaults, and a `nextAction` hint."],[1346,"Bind address (default `127.0.0.1`)"],[231,"Board + lanes with per-lane ticket counts + the decorated work items in scope."],[150,"Boards"],[1438,"Boards"],[1246,"Boards and portable definitions"],[1278,"Boards are configured software-factory views over work items. Board **definitions** are portable JSON documents describing a whole kanban — lanes, guards, triggers, transition policy, and optional schedule hookups. Agents provision boards from these documents; the DB row is one instance of a definition."],[832,"Body: `{ runId }`."],[835,"Body: `{ runId }`."],[693,"Bootstrap token"],[1122,"Bot setup"],[1616,"Both operations require an admin-scoped token."],[758,"Browser session bootstrap (rate-limited)."],[694,"Browser sessions"],[440,"Budgets"],[459,"Budgets are hard stops, not advisories:"],[920,"Building agents on Runyard"],[1475,"Builds and pushes GHCR `hub` and `runner` container images behind the same two gates, and records both image digests as a release artifact."],[119,"By default a card is blocking: nothing happens until someone decides. Supplying `timeoutMs` or `timeoutAt` at creation makes it a **timed approval**:"],[503,"By default the runner executes workflows directly on its host. Setting `RUNNER_SANDBOX=bubblewrap` on the runner wraps each workflow *launch* in a generated Bubblewrap (`bwrap`) sandbox: the run's workspace is the only writable mount (bound at the same path inside and out), system directories are bound read-only, and the child gets a fresh workspace-local `HOME` — the host home directory, with its keys and credentials, is never mounted. Polling and control commands stay outside the sandbox. Installing `bwrap` is the deployer's responsibility; the runner verifies at startup that the sandbox actually works before claiming runs."],[1044,"Cancel; re-queue with same/edited input; merge a successful isolated run into its target branch"],[201,"Cancelling is already an operator act."],[792,"Cannot progress without a specific intervention (`blockedReason` says which)."],[994,"Canonical"],[489,"Capacity and pool"],[441,"Capture paths: what is metered today"],[1138,"Cards are posted to the configured chat with inline buttons (see below)."],[1185,"Cards can deep-link into the Hub as a Telegram WebApp. `POST /api/auth/telegram-webapp` exchanges the WebApp's signed init data for a browser session that is limited to the `approvals` scope — a Telegram identity can review and resolve approval cards, and nothing else. Full app access always requires a real access token."],[47,"Catalog"],[1434,"Catalog"],[1626,"Catalog grouping (for example `Examples`, `Operations`)."],[1221,"Cause / fix"],[205,"Channel"],[1175,"Chat (group or DM) where approval cards are posted."],[277,"Check *content*: status, conclusion, annotations, deep links"],[276,"Check *display* on commits/PRs"],[290,"Check conclusion"],[1567,"Check run diagnostics; fix workflow config or runner setup."],[1234,"Check stuck `queued` on GitHub"],[261,"CI"],[306,"CI infrastructure problem (e.g. Dagger missing) — not a code failure"],[282,"CI is SHA-pinned. Provenance distinguishes four things: the provider-reported **head SHA**, the **base SHA** (target branch at receipt time), the **tested checkout**, and the **check target** (always the head SHA). For pull requests the runner constructs the merge candidate deterministically — fetch the pinned base and head, merge head into base — so *every job of a pipeline tests the identical tree*, and CI honestly tests the integration result rather than the raw branch head. A conflicted merge is a first-class blocked conclusion (`action_required` on the check), never a silent fallback to testing the head."],[1455,"CI pipeline"],[1186,"CI setup"],[543,"Claimed by a runner, not yet started."],[1330,"claims runs and executes them; workspace volume at `/workspace`"],[1559,"Class"],[764,"Clears the session cookie."],[1133,"CLI"],[1239,"CLI"],[1487,"CLI"],[1115,"CLI guide — the same API from your terminal"],[34,"CLI:"],[259,"CLI:"],[454,"CLI: `runyard usage` (fleet rollup) and `runyard usage <runId>` (one run's detail)."],[839,"CLI: `runyard work` (board list), `runyard work-item show|create|update|link|unlink`, `runyard flow <runId>`, and `runyard run <workflow> --work-item <id>`."],[1516,"Client install assets."],[800,"Closed historical item (hidden from lists by default)."],[1177,"Comma-separated Telegram user ids allowed to resolve approvals."],[294,"Commands exited 0"],[148,"Comment describes the requested changes."],[1229,"Commit the config to the default branch (PRs read it from the base)."],[1212,"Committed to the repository (loaded from the **trusted base** revision, pinned by SHA). The schema is deliberately small — it is not GitHub Actions:"],[1556,"Common causes: the runner unit is idling because `RUNYARD_HUB_TOKEN` is empty or revoked; the runner's tags do not include what the workflow requires (`requiredRunnerTags`, for example `smithers`); or the run asked for `--where local` and only `vps` runners are registered. Running `runyard preflight <workflow>` before enqueueing catches `no_matching_runner` up front."],[418,"Concepts"],[1297,"Confidential VMs (dstack / Intel TDX)"],[798,"Confirmed to satisfy the original ask."],[1385,"Connect AI agents to a Runyard Hub with the runyard-mcp stdio server and its 87-tool surface."],[1242,"Connecting to a Hub"],[262,"Continuous integration on RunYard runners — GitHub stays the canonical repo host; RunYard verifies every change with SHA-pinned, trust-aware pipelines."],[422,"Control"],[1328,"control plane + web UI + embedded datastore (HTTP on `PORT`, default 8080 in-container)"],[375,"Copy verified artifacts to a configured target root (optionally with a public URL base)."],[470,"Coverage"],[1083,"Create + preflight a draft: `{workflow, input, executionMode}` → `201` with status `ready` / `needs_input` / `blocked` and open questions"],[1169,"Create a bot with Telegram's BotFather, then configure the Hub through environment variables (values belong in your env file or secret store — never in code or docs):"],[1072,"Create a card: `{title, description, runId?, ask, timeoutMs?/timeoutAt? + fallback?}` for timed approvals"],[1199,"Create a GitHub App (Settings → Developer settings → GitHub Apps → New) owned by your user or org:"],[1608,"Create and edit workflows by sending source bytes over the API or MCP; the Hub stores them as immutable, versioned bundles."],[1528,"Create and resolve approval cards (the scope Telegram WebApp sessions get)."],[1642,"Create the workflow by sending that source inline as `workflow.source` (a JSON string — the TSX above, escaped):"],[252,"Create-or-update the board and reconcile schedule hookups."],[1030,"Create/update a workflow (admin). Source is submitted as bytes or a `workflow.bundleId` — never a file path"],[612,"Cron and one-shot triggers that create ordinary workflow runs on a cadence."],[613,"Cron expressions and timezones"],[1194,"Dagger executor"],[724,"Dashboards, monitors, and cautious integrations that must never change state."],[1350,"Data directory (default `<repo>/data`) — the DB, artifacts, and bootstrap token live here"],[845,"DB-backed workflow bundles"],[318,"Deep Links"],[321,"Deep links in API payloads"],[843,"Definition"],[1609,"Definition anatomy"],[885,"Definition and input schema."],[1226,"Delivery recorded as `ignored: repository … not enabled`"],[279,"Delivery verification, dedupe, and the receipt ledger"],[315,"Denied by trust policy (e.g. native on a fork)"],[1311,"Dependency install and build (`corepack enable` works)"],[1022,"Describe a workflow and its input schema"],[867,"Disabled workflows disappear from the catalog for non-admins and cannot be run."],[1243,"Discover and run workflows"],[960,"Discovery"],[1404,"Discovery & identity"],[922,"Discovery surfaces"],[921,"Discovery surfaces, the API-first guarantee, and recommended etiquette for agents and third-party clients."],[1360,"Display name of the deployment (default `Runyard`)"],[1615,"Do NOT write workflow files to disk: custom workflow definitions that reference bare `workflow.entry` file paths without source bytes are rejected (`workflow_source_required`). Repository-authored workflow files are reserved for the shipped internal/dev seed catalog only. The web app's workflow editor is not an exception — it calls these same API endpoints."],[1296,"Docker Compose"],[1458,"Docs stay current"],[1079,"Drafts make run-creation negotiation explicit: a draft is a proposed run that\nhas **not** been enqueued, and its status mirrors the latest preflight."],[1383,"Drive it over HTTP: API guide"],[1026,"Dry-run preflight: `ready` / `needs_input` / `blocked`, nothing created"],[151,"Durable configured views over work items — the software-factory surfaces that workflows keep up to date."],[1139,"Each card takes one of three decisions:"],[26,"Each deployment serves its own CLI install script:"],[802,"Each item also carries `type` (`feature`, `bug`, `research`, `release`, `maintenance`, `idea`), `priority` (`urgent`, `high`, `normal`, `low`), `project`, `owner`/`requester`, `acceptanceCriteria`, `nextAction`, `blockedReason`, and an optional `dueAt`."],[1184,"Each pending card is posted as a message carrying the ask (what approving does, why a human is needed), a sanitized input summary, and inline buttons: **Approve**, **Request changes**, **Reject**. Only the configured approval user ids can act; a button press resolves the card exactly like the web or API would, and the message is edited to show the resolution (\"Approved by ... at ...\") with the buttons removed."],[371,"Each profile has a fixed `kind` with a fixed set of config keys — anything else is rejected, so raw credentials or ad-hoc shell fragments can never be smuggled into a profile:"],[502,"Each runner declares a `capacity` (concurrent run slots) and reports its active runs; the Hub assigns work only to free slots. `GET /api/runners` returns every registered runner with heartbeat state, capacity, active slots, plus a pool summary — the same data the **Runners** page in the web app shows (`#runners`)."],[629,"Each schedule tracks `nextRunAt`, `lastRunAt`, the last run id, and the last run's current terminal status, all visible on the Schedules page (`#schedules`) and in the API. Enabled schedules must target an enabled workflow. If a workflow is disabled later, RunYard fails safe: dependent enabled schedules are atomically auto-disabled, keep their history, and expose `state: \"broken\"`, `brokenReason`, `disabledReason`, and `operatorAction` in API/MCP/Web payloads. Re-enable only after editing the schedule to an enabled workflow."],[348,"Edit the workflow (admin)."],[373,"Effect"],[182,"Enable the schedule only on a Hub where daily proposal runs are desired. Importing the definition in tests or dev keeps it disabled so it cannot create unsolicited runs."],[616,"Enable, disable, run now"],[848,"Enabled and disabled"],[1057,"Encrypted secrets store — names and metadata only, never values (admin)"],[59,"Endpoint"],[128,"Endpoint"],[223,"Endpoint"],[404,"Endpoint"],[504,"Endpoint"],[580,"Endpoint"],[633,"Endpoint"],[677,"Endpoint"],[738,"Endpoint"],[812,"Endpoint"],[874,"Endpoint"],[1104,"Endpoint"],[1503,"Endpoint"],[217,"Enforcement runs on **every board whose project scope covers the ticket**. A denial from any board rejects the PATCH with `409 Conflict`, the board's `message`, and the offending `{from, to}` transition. Callers driving a move on behalf of a workflow or run should declare it on the PATCH body:"],[1299,"Environment variables"],[1256,"Environment variables `RUNYARD_HUB_URL` / `RUNYARD_HUB_TOKEN` (and an explicit\n`--url` / `--token`) take precedence over the saved remote."],[1219,"Equivalent HTTP endpoints live in the `ci` API group (`/api/v1/ci/...`), and MCP tools `list_ci_repositories`, `get_ci_pipeline`, `dispatch_ci_run` cover agent use. Admin diagnostics: `GET /api/ci/deliveries` (webhook ledger) and `GET /api/ci/diagnostics` (signature failures, duplicates, queue latency, check lag). After a GitHub outage, `POST /api/ci/pipelines/:id/sync-checks` resets the bounded check-retry counters and reconciles."],[966,"Error conventions"],[531,"Events, timeline, logs, artifacts"],[465,"Every budgeted run also carries a computed &#x2A;*`budgetStatus`** — spent vs limit, per dimension — so no client re-derives the arithmetic:"],[122,"Every card answers \"what will my decision do\" honestly, computed from what resolving actually performs:"],[478,"Every claude / codex / pi CLI call the Smithers engine reports via its structured `TokenUsageReported` events"],[160,"Every deployment seeds one default board on first boot — &#x2A;\"\\<instance name> Factory\"* (slug `runyard` by default) — so the Work view is a configured product surface from day one, never an empty shell. More boards can be created for product, infra,