,[153,"RunYard dogfooding loop"],[1302,"Runyard is a self-hosted control plane for agent runs. A deployment has a small,\nfixed shape:"],[4,"Runyard is a self-hosted control plane for agent runs. Agents and humans trigger workflows over MCP, the CLI, the HTTP API, or the web app; runners execute those workflows with the Smithers engine; and the Hub stores the durable record of everything that happened — runs, logs, events, artifacts, approvals, and knowledge. A run started from a chat agent, a cron schedule, or a terminal all leaves the same auditable trail in the same place."],[424,"Runyard is a self-hosted control plane for agent runs. You install **workflows** into a catalog, start **runs** of those workflows from the API, MCP, web app, or a **schedule**, and **runners** claim and execute them. The durable company asks those runs work on are **work items** — tickets on the Work board. Anything that needs a human decision surfaces as an **approval** card, sensitive values live in the encrypted **secrets** store, and optional side effects after a run are handled by admin-defined **hooks**. Access is governed by scoped **tokens**, and every page in the Hub is a shareable **deep link**."],[6,"Runyard is API-first by construction. Every HTTP route the Hub serves is declared in a single API surface registry; the OpenAPI document is generated from it and the MCP tool list is parity-tested against it. The web app is an ordinary API client with no privileged endpoints — anything it can show or do is equally available over the API and MCP, so a third-party client built on those surfaces loses nothing."],[5,"Runyard is designed as one private deployment per company. Your Hub holds your workflow catalog, your secrets, your runners, and your history; nothing about your deployment is published to a shared service, and the only outbound call the Hub makes is a passive read of the public GitHub Releases API to check for updates. Operators, teammates, and their agents all authenticate to the same Hub with scoped access tokens."],[1501,"Runyard is one private deployment per company, and the security model follows from that: a small, deliberate unauthenticated surface; scoped bearer tokens for everything else; secrets encrypted at rest and never echoed; and approval gates in front of dangerous work."],[667,"Runyard keeps reusable credentials (API keys, deploy tokens) in an **encrypted secret store** on the Hub. Values are encrypted at rest, and the API is deliberately one-way: you can list secret *names and metadata*, set a value, and delete one — **values are never returned** by any list or read endpoint, to any scope."],[271,"RunYard owns"],[1324,"Runyard publishes two environment-agnostic images to GHCR:"],[1459,"Runyard releases are semver git tags (`vX.Y.Z`). The version in `package.json` is the single source of truth and flows to `/api/version`, the OpenAPI document, the CLI, and the update checker."],[1490,"Runyard ships a repo-agnostic `docs-update` workflow that keeps documentation honest against each release. When a release is published, a GitHub Actions step triggers it on the project's own Hub through an authenticated workflow endpoint (`release-docs-update`); the workflow inspects only the git diff between the previous and new release tags — never the whole repository — and reports proposed documentation updates. In its opt-in `apply` mode it edits docs in an isolated worktree branch instead, and that branch reaches the target branch only through a human-approved run promotion. The repository, docs path, docs framework, and file-selection rules are all workflow inputs, so any repo can adopt it."],[928,"Runyard treats agents as first-class API consumers. This page covers how a client discovers what a Hub can do, what it may rely on, and how to be a good citizen."],[621,"Runyard uses standard **5-field cron** (`minute hour day-of-month month day-of-week`) with ranges (`a-b`), lists (`a,b,c`), steps (`*/n`, `a-b/n`), month/weekday names (`jan..dec`, `sun..sat`), and the aliases `@yearly`, `@monthly`, `@weekly`, `@daily`, `@hourly`. There is no seconds field — the Hub ticks at minute granularity."],[1214,"RunYard's own repository carries a working example at `.runyard/ci.yml`."],[1468,"Same"],[490,"Sandboxing"],[611,"Schedules"],[1414,"Schedules"],[352,"Schedules / one schedule."],[615,"Schedules from board definitions"],[249,"Schema check without touching the DB."],[700,"Scope"],[972,"Scope"],[1519,"Scope"],[691,"Scopes"],[717,"Scopes"],[1494,"Scopes"],[1354,"Secret for browser session cookies. Required in production; in dev a generated value is persisted to the data dir"],[668,"Secret names are env-var-safe identifiers, because that is exactly how they are delivered. The whole feature is gated on the store being enabled (an encryption key configured on the Hub); when it is not, secret-dependent runs and hooks report that configuration is required instead of failing obscurely."],[1179,"Secret Telegram echoes back so the Hub can verify webhook calls."],[662,"Secrets"],[1424,"Secrets"],[1495,"Secrets"],[673,"Secrets never appear in run events, logs, or the run record."],[1550,"Secrets not configured"],[1491,"Security model"],[1337,"See `deploy/dstack/README.md` in the repository for the full contract."],[1235,"See `GET /api/ci/diagnostics` → check lag; after an outage run `sync-checks`. Reporter failures never affect the run itself."],[968,"See also"],[317,"See the CI setup guide for GitHub App registration, `.runyard/ci.yml` reference, runner setup, and troubleshooting."],[1287,"See the MCP guide for clients and options."],[359,"Segments are URL-encoded, so ids and slugs with special characters remain valid links. Some tabs accept aliases (for example `visual` for `graph`, `source` for `code`)."],[442,"Selecting gateway metering"],[367,"Selecting hooks per run"],[385,"Selection is explicit and two-sided:"],[1457,"Self-update for deployments"],[970,"Send an access token as a bearer token on ever